<promed@promedmail.org>
[In general the fall in sea turtle numbers, especially in the Gulf of
Mexico, has been ascribed to shrimp nets, a major problem. Without sound
denominators (always a problem with wildlife population studies) it is hard
to interpret numerators such as animals found dead or sick and therefore
whether something is getting worse or better. Probably the only reliable
number is the number of egg-laying landing adult female turtles. Boats are
also a major problem for manatees in Florida. Florida wildlife authorities
have begun to release baby turtles offshore in hopes of offsetting the high
losses when they enter the surf from birds and other predators awaiting
them. As they mature slowly, it will be a decade or so before any benefits
may be observed. Comments on this report are welcomed. - Mod.MHJ]
